I worked up until I went into labor and delivered my daughter that same day. My first day of leave was her birthday 2/22/17 and I returned to work 6/1/17. I had 4 weeks left of leave to my disposable, however due to lack of income I chose to return to work ealier. Those 4 weeks of leave expired on my daughters first birthday, so I decided to use them the end of Jan into Feb. 2018.

column37: the minute we started introducing other food to her diet at around 5 months 07/01/17
column43: She started daycare at about 1 year old, and truthfully i feel so blessed to have had a year with her. mainly because i see she is a self confidant toddler now.
Received 8 weeks pay (55% from SDI) then took 2 months unpaid
It was 50% teaching load as opposed to 100%. I was not completely off of work but this was for summer and 15 weeks in the Fall.
I took three consecutive months off of work after the birth of my baby and then selected to take baby bonding days (Wednesdays off) intermittently for 30 days after that.

I used a combination of paid leave funded through state disability and accumulated vacation days from my job for a total of about 12 weeks. I would love to have had even more time off with my new family.
I am grateful for the time because I know many women do not get as much as I did, but I know my baby and I would have benefitted from more time. I was not emotionally ready to go back to work.
I was not employed 3 months before I gave birth to my baby. I don't have work since then.
I quit my job before getting pregnant and became a homemaker. I've been home ever since and have loved being a stay-at-home mom!
It was a great time to bond with my wife, and support her in recovery and with the baby.

I'm a teacher, tutor, movie programmer, and filmmaker. So I basically carved out 2 free days then worked to be home as often as I could while still working daily. I've always taken Sundays off entirely to be with my wife and son.
I would have loved to stay longer with my son, but I'm grateful that I had the time that I did.
Went from working to not working and full time mom
I did not return to work full-time, only one day a week

I enjoy my job a lot and am very fulfilled by it, and in some ways I was excited to return to work and see my coworkers (who are also good friends), but I was very torn about leaving my baby and definitely would have wanted to have more time at home with him. I would say at least six months, or perhaps a staggered return to work over a few months (which isn't really an option in my position). I struggle a lot being away from him now that I am back at work.
I wish I could have spent more time bonding with my new addition and helping my wife with this big life change. My wife and I had to alternate leave to support us.
I had a lower back injury and was in disability pay/leave for 2 months
I took off three months, but I believe an additional month would have been helpful.
Wasnt long enough. My job made me feel like it wasnt important for me to take off because I wasnt the one having the baby...

I began an internship 2 months postpartum (I accepted the position while pregnant) but later deeply regretted it as it felt far too soon to begin a new job that required commuting an hour each way twice a week, while still juggling my other responsibilities for my other position, while breastfeeding and pumping all day. It was very very difficult and overwhelming both physically and emotionally
I wish I took more time off. And used the 6 week given by the state.
none
I was going to school and we happened to have the baby born on summer brake.

I took one month of official maternity leave, but I was on a research block in my my medical residency so i took one additional month of working from home, and then returned to half time for another two months.
I decided to take a job opportunity out of state 3 weeks after my son was born. the opportunity lasted about 2 months before I decided to come back home. I regret leaving my son in those early days.
I am blessed enough to have been able to work part time  and spend the last year with my son.

I wish I could have taken more time off, I had a difficult time returning to work. It was stressful to leave her at 4 months, I had a hard time keeping up with breastfeeding, exhausted from be up every few hours at night and I got really sick with a reoccurring digestive issue I have. The baby didn't start sleeping through the night until 7 months. I would have like to return then. I feel like I would have been more ready.
Wish to spend more time off with my baby.
I quit my job after maternity leave ended to stay at home with my baby
I took 6 weeks paid leave
I wish I had 6 mo of paid maternity leave.
I wish my employer and more employers offered paid paternity leave.
I had planned to return to work when our baby was about 6 months old but I still have not and dont plan to anymore.
I originally took 3 months off, but then ended up quitting my job to stay home with the baby full time.
I work freelance so the amount of time take off work is a factor of how much i feel like taking off and what jobs present themselves.  In that time however I didn't have any new jobs to take on.
I would have liked to take off at least one additional month

I was originally planning on only taking 4 months, but I extended it by a month due to my baby experiencing a lot of colic/feeding problems and struggling with this. Later, I was hoping to take 6 full weeks off of unpaid leave through the state, but Covid occurred, and I felt too confined to the home, so opted to go back to work after 3 weeks.

column626: It has been a change for sure, but I believe it has brought my relationship with my daughter and fiance closer together

column43: I lost my job shortly before the birth of my baby and haven't had a new job since. So I am technically not on maternity leave, although I am home with my baby until we feel the need for me to go back to work.
column626: I was talking to a friend the other day when I said "this is not how your first year as a mom is supposed to go. The first year is so hard and draining and you expect help and to be able to meet with other moms and babies and go to support groups, do retail therapy, take your baby to the park or beach, have relatives visit, and so on. Instead I have been completely isolated with my baby these last few months. New moms are under so much mental stress and pressure as it is, but with covid and being isolated to the extreme you go absolutely crazy. You feel so lonely and overwhelmed, and you were supposed to be able to meet with other moms to support each other."

column43: Quit my teaching job during my pregnancy because of stress from my work.
column626: Weve been strict about quarantine to keep ourselves healthy. It has created some anxiety when weve had to go out of our home. I have also started seeing a therapist to help me with my anxiety and thats helped me a lot during this quarantine.

column43: Wish I can take more time off to spend with my kid.
column626: Makes me want to be housewife because of feeling pressure from my boss to work in the office

column43: Due to the pandemic I am able to stay home and work from home. I get to enjoy watching my son grow.
column626: I have enjoyed seeing my baby grow and all his milestones .

column43: My company actually didn't offer official paternity leave benefits, but my boss and my team were cool and allowed me to "work from home" for two weeks (this was before COVID so work from home wasn't as common)
column626: We have only had one date night where someone else looked after the baby in the last year

column43: Due to COVID stay at home order, I ended up not going back to the office when I returned to work. My maternity leave ended just as we started working from home so I have been with my son the entire first year even though I have been working from home for the last 8 months.

column626: It has greatly improved my parenting experience because I get to spend much more time with my daughter than I would have in a normal year. Worked from home, then lost job, but get to be in my daughter's life more.
It's been good in that my partner and I have been able to spend far more time with our baby than we would have, but it's also exhausting because we have less help and are working from home.

12 weeks is not nearly enough!

column626: The pandemic has been negative in many ways, but staying home and spending more time with my baby has helped strengthen our bond.

column43: I didn't tale any time off because I am self-employed (and under-employed). This effectively allows me to share in baby responsibilities and not feel overburdened by work.
column626: it's hard to determine how it's impacted things, since COVID hit shortly after she was born.

column43: If we were not in stay at home order I would have been very sad to return to work in the office. My post partum depression and anxiety would not have healed as well as it did with the time I was able to spend with my baby.

I wish America let parents take more time off of work - it's ridiculous. My employer paid for 8 weeks and that's considered generous. Generous? 8 weeks? My child is still a blob and barely sorting out night and day. I took an additional 4 weeks off - unpaid by my employer. America is killing parents.
column626: It's so lonely. No one can come over to meet our child or drop off food. Her huge milestones only happen on Instagram. It's been a hard year and I've started therapy because of it.

column43: I think both parents should get a year off of work to bond with baby and get their family routine down. The 3 months I had were great but having it be mostly unpaid is bullshit. I never thought about it til I had a baby but I hope going forward all future parents get paid time to be with baby.
column612: Mask up at the park with Daddy and Me class
column626: I am not a sociopath (I think) but the pandemic has made me less willing to pander to others needs to seek attachment to my kid. Like, if there was no Covid I think we could get coaxed out of the house more "for the gram" so folk to take pictures with my baby. Now all of that is gone and if I want to see folks(now and also earlier in my child's life) I will or they will go the extra mile to see the baby.  One other thing is that my child was born at the very start of the pandemic (as far as the USA is concerned, early March 2020). We had meal trains lined up for us and grandparents and aunts and uncles willing to come down and help via cleaning the home, laundry, cooking etc . None of that happened for a while and it was HARD. Parenting is hard regardless but that isolation without even a 20 minute reprieve really wore on us at the start of the pandemic when no one knew anything (like can you get it from a doorknob? Will it hurt your child?!?) I could go on, mostly I do enjoy not seeing people and having an excuse but really and especially the anti Mask simpletons I encountered at my restaurant job. Overall I love being with my wife and baby girl and the pandemic has helped me really get a routine going for our family/home more so than if I had to work my normal 50-60 hours a week away from them.
